{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"08720d4f32a0530b","type":"text","text":"## Second Normal Form (2NF): \"No Partial Dependencies\"\n\n**The Rule:** It must be in 1NF, and every non-key column must depend on the **entire** primary key. This mostly applies when you have a \"Composite Key\" (a key made of two columns).\n\n- **Example:** Imagine a table called `Project_Assignments`. The Primary Key is `(Project_ID + Engineer_ID)`.\n    \n- **Bad (Not 2NF):** If you include `Engineer_Phone_Number` in this table.\n    \n    - _The Problem:_ The phone number only depends on the `Engineer_ID`, not the `Project_ID`. If the engineer leaves the project, you lose their phone number, or if they are on 10 projects, you’ve typed their phone number 10 times.\n        \n- **Good (2NF):** Move `Engineer_Phone_Number` to a separate `Engineers` table.\n    \n    - _Obsidian equivalent:_ Don't put the \"Wizer Office Address\" inside every single note about a Wizer task. Create a `Wizer.md` note with the address and **link** to it.","x":101,"y":-320,"width":799,"height":540},
		{"id":"7bfef8ea32fdb224","type":"text","text":"## Third Normal Form (3NF): \"No Transitive Dependencies\"\n\n**The Rule:** It must be in 2NF, and no non-key column should depend on _another_ non-key column. Everything must depend **only** on the Primary Key.\n\n> **The Famous Saying:** \"The data must depend on the Key, the Whole Key, and Nothing But the Key (so help me Codd).\"\n\n- **Example:** A `Users` table with `User_ID` (Key), `Name`, `City`, and `City_Zip_Code`.\n    \n- **The Problem:** `City_Zip_Code` depends on the `City`, not the `User_ID`. This is a \"transitive\" dependency ($User \\to City \\to Zip$).\n    \n    - If you change the Zip Code for \"Tbilisi,\" you have to update every single user living there. That's a recipe for bugs.\n        \n- **The Fix (3NF):** 1. Table 1: `Users [User_ID, Name, City_ID]`\n    \n    2. Table 2: `Cities [City_ID, City_Name, Zip_Code]`\n    \n- **Obsidian logic:** This is exactly why we use **Links (`[[ ]]`)**. Instead of typing the \"Project Manager's Email\" in every Task note, you link to the `Project.md` note. The email \"depends\" on the Project, not the Task.","x":960,"y":-320,"width":816,"height":500},
		{"id":"cfa59762e2371ca3","type":"file","file":"Pasted image 20260403150754.png","x":-68,"y":320,"width":1137,"height":760},
		{"id":"ce199a55e3267f16","type":"text","text":"https://www.youtube.com/shorts/fIJaCpDrtL0","x":200,"y":-480,"width":434,"height":53},
		{"id":"ceafc236e957ecc9","type":"text","text":"## First Normal Form (1NF): \"Atomic Values\"\n\n**The Rule:** Each \"cell\" or field must contain only one value, and there should be no repeating groups.\n\n- **Bad (Not 1NF):** You have a note for a project, and in the `tags` field, you put `[NodeJS, Postgres, Wizer]`. If you want to search _only_ for \"Postgres\" projects, the database has to \"split\" that string every time.\n    \n- **Good (1NF):** Each tag is its own entry. In a database table, this means you don't store a comma-separated list; you store one row per tag.\n    \n    - _Obsidian equivalent:_ Using separate properties for each piece of data rather than one big \"Notes\" block containing IDs and dates mixed together.","x":-560,"y":-280,"width":608,"height":421},
		{"id":"d8ab6e71671bb411","type":"text","text":"### 1NF: First Normal Form\n\n**Goal:** Eliminate duplicate columns and ensure atomicity.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Each column must contain **atomic** (indivisible) values. No lists or sets.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** Each column must have a unique name.\n    \n- **Rule 3:** Data must be organized into tables with a defined **Primary Key**.\n    \n\n### 2NF: Second Normal Form\n\n**Goal:** Eliminate partial dependencies.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Must already satisfy **1NF**.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** All non-key attributes must be **fully functional dependent** on the entire Primary Key. (If you have a composite key, a column cannot depend on just _part_ of that key).\n    \n\n### 3NF: Third Normal Form\n\n**Goal:** Eliminate transitive dependencies.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Must already satisfy **2NF**.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** No non-key attribute should depend on another non-key attribute. Every column must depend **\"only on the key, the whole key, and nothing but the key.\"**\n    \n\n### BCNF: Boyce-Codd Normal Form\n\n**Goal:** Fix anomalies where a table has multiple overlapping candidate keys.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Must already satisfy **3NF**.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** For every functional dependency $X \\rightarrow Y$, $X$ must be a **superkey**. (Basically, a \"stronger\" version of 3NF).\n    \n\n### 4NF: Fourth Normal Form\n\n**Goal:** Eliminate multi-valued dependencies.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Must already satisfy **BCNF**.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** A table cannot contain two or more **independent multi-valued facts** about an entity. (e.g., if one person has multiple phone numbers and multiple email addresses, they shouldn't be in the same table if they aren't related to each other).\n    \n\n### 5NF: Fifth Normal Form (Project-Join NF)\n\n**Goal:** Eliminate join dependencies.\n\n- **Rule 1:** Must already satisfy **4NF**.\n    \n- **Rule 2:** The table cannot be decomposed into smaller tables that, when joined back together, create \"spurious\" (incorrect) data. Every join dependency in the table must be a consequence of the candidate keys.","x":-68,"y":1120,"width":995,"height":1199},
		{"id":"bcac6571a88a6946","type":"text","text":"## 1NF: The \"One Item Per Spot\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** You put a pile of LEGOs, a Barbie, and a sandwich all in one single cubby.\n\n- **The Fix:** Every cubby can only hold **one** thing. No piles, no bags of mixed stuff. Just one item, one spot.\n    \n\n## 2NF: The \"Don't Be a Half-Helper\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** You have a sticker that says \"Big Red Truck,\" but you put it on a box that only holds \"Trucks.\" If you move the box, the \"Big Red\" part doesn't make sense anymore.\n\n- **The Fix:** If a label describes something, it has to describe the **whole** thing, not just a little piece of it.\n    \n\n## 3NF: The \"No Gossip\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** You have a list that says \"The Ball is Blue\" and \"Blue is a Pretty Color.\"\n\n- **The Fix:** The list should only be about the Ball. If you want to talk about how \"Blue is Pretty,\" go tell that to a different list. Don't let your facts rely on other facts.\n    \n\n## BCNF: The \"Bosses Only\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** A \"helper\" item is trying to tell the \"Primary Key\" item what to do.\n\n- **The Fix:** Only the **Big Boss** (the Key) is allowed to decide what the other information in the row looks like. No \"secret bosses\" allowed.\n    \n\n## 4NF: The \"Don't Mix Your Hobbies\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** You make a list of \"Friends who like Pizza\" and \"Friends who like Batman\" in the same chart. It gets confusing because some like both, and some like one.\n\n- **The Fix:** Keep your \"Pizza Friends\" list and your \"Batman Friends\" list **separate**. Don't mash two different \"multi-choice\" lists together.\n    \n\n## 5NF: The \"Puzzle Piece\" Rule\n\n**The Problem:** You break a big LEGO castle into three parts, but when you snap them back together, it turns into a weird boat that wasn't there before.\n\n- **The Fix:** Only break things apart if you can put them back together **exactly** like they were, with no \"ghost\" pieces appearing out of nowhere.","x":-52,"y":-1720,"width":1332,"height":1160}
	],
